{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "11 — Local Inference: The Embedded Kronk Engine",
  "description": "How a user turn gets a language model. This tour follows the path from the single provider-agnostic llm.Client interface, through model enumeration and provider routing in internal/turn, down into the in-process Kronk engine (llama.cpp via yzma, dlopen'd at runtime, CGO_ENABLED=0), and out to runtime installation, the curated EU model catalog, and the resumable model downloader. The opt-in remote path is shown where it branches off so you can see what stays local and what does not.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 44,
      "title": "11.1 — The one seam",
      "description": "```go\ntype Client interface {\n    ChatStream(ctx context.Context, msgs []Message, tools []ToolSpec) (<-chan Chunk, error)\n    Embed(ctx context.Context, texts []string) ([][]float32, error)\n}\n```\n\nEvery caller above this line — the agent loop, the turn pipeline, the embed helper — is **provider-agnostic**. They hold a `llm.Client` and never know whether they are talking to an in-process GGUF model or a remote HTTP endpoint.\n\nTwo methods only:\n- `ChatStream` — streams the reply as `Chunk` values on a channel; the channel closes on `Done` or `Err`. Implementations must honour ctx cancellation.\n- `Embed` — returns one float32 vector per input text; used by the recall pipeline for semantic search.\n\nAGENTS.md invariant: *local is the default provider path and stays first-class.* The interface has no notion of locality — that is resolved one layer down in `internal/turn`.\n\n**Tour 01** covers the full `internal/llm` type set (Message, Chunk, ToolSpec). **Tour 03** shows the agent loop that calls ChatStream."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/turn/models.go",
      "line": 61,
      "title": "11.2 — What models exist",
      "description": "```go\nfunc ModelChoices(app core.App) ([]ModelChoice, ModelChoice, error)\n```\n\n`ModelChoices` enumerates every model registered in PocketBase and resolves which one is currently active. It is the single function the Models page and the turn pipeline both call — one source of truth for what the owner has configured.\n\nThe resolution is **explicit and non-silent**: if no saved choice matches an available, non-disabled model, the active slot is left empty and the caller gets an error from `ActiveModelChoice`. There is no hidden fallback to a default cloud model.\n\nA local model is marked `Disabled` when its GGUF file is absent from disk (`os.Stat` fails). A legacy Ollama tag (non-GGUF local entry from before plan 074) is always disabled because there is no engine to run it.\n\n`store.EnsureDefaultLLMConfig` seeds the first local model entry if the owner has not yet configured anything — providing a sensible starting point without forcing a decision.\n\n**Tour 12** covers `internal/store` and LLM config storage. **Tour 05** shows how the turn pipeline calls `ActiveModelChoice`."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/turn/models.go",
      "line": 168,
      "title": "11.3 — Choice to client",
      "description": "```go\ntype ClientSource struct {\n    Engine *kronk.Engine\n}\n```\n\n`ClientSource` is the bridge between a `ModelChoice` and a live `llm.Client`. It holds a reference to the in-process Kronk `Engine` and routes based on the provider kind stored in the config record.\n\nThe routing in `clientForConfig` (line 207) has exactly two branches:\n- **`\"local\"`** — GGUF file path → `s.Engine.Client(chatPath, embedPath)`. The engine is the in-process Kronk runtime; nothing leaves the machine.\n- **`\"openai\"`** — base URL + API key → `llm.OpenAIClient{…}`. This is the opt-in, consent-gated remote path; the owner must explicitly add and select a cloud model from the Models page. Embeddings always stay local — the OpenAI client's `Embed` method is never called on the default recall path.\n\nThere is no silent auto-routing and no third branch. AGENTS.md invariant: *a turn only leaves the box on the owner's explicit, confirmed selection.*\n\nThe test `TestClientSourceLocalGGUFUsesKronk` (in `internal/turn/models_test.go`) pins this routing contract."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/engine.go",
      "line": 52,
      "title": "11.4 — The resident engine",
      "description": "```go\nfunc NewEngine(libPath, processor string) *Engine\n```\n\n`Engine` owns two resident `*kronk.Kronk` model slots — one for chat, one for embeddings — each loaded lazily on first use and held in memory for the process lifetime. A `sync.Mutex` guards all load/unload operations.\n\n`NewEngine` takes a lib path and processor tag (`cpu` or `vulkan`) and returns an `Engine` that is **not yet initialised**. No library is loaded, no model is loaded. A box with no GGUF file and no native library still boots cleanly.\n\n`ensureInit` (line 73) runs `kronk.Init` at most once per process — it resolves the correct `<os>/<arch>/<processor>/` directory under `LibRoot()`, then calls `kronk.Init(kronk.WithLibPath(…))` which `dlopen`s the llama.cpp shared library. This is the moment the native code enters the process. After that, individual models are loaded on demand by `chatModel` and `embedModel`.\n\n`Close` (line 179) calls `Unload` on both resident slots and is wired to the `OnTerminate` hook in `main.go` — clean shutdown, no leaked handles.\n\nCGO stays off throughout: llama.cpp is a pre-built `.so` loaded at runtime by yzma (the Kronk SDK's purego bridge), so `CGO_ENABLED=0` holds for every `go build` invocation.\n\n**Tour 00** step 0.1 introduces the one-binary architecture that makes this in-process design possible."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/client.go",
      "line": 41,
      "title": "11.5 — Bridging to llm.Client",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (c *Client) ChatStream(ctx context.Context, msgs []llm.Message, tools []llm.ToolSpec) (<-chan llm.Chunk, error)\n```\n\n`kronk.Client` implements `llm.Client` against the resident `Engine` models. `ChatStream` does four things:\n\n1. **Acquire the chat model** — calls `c.eng.chatModel(ctx, c.chatPath)`, which lazy-loads the GGUF file if it is not already resident. Swap to a different model path and the engine loads the new file, unloading the old one.\n2. **Inject a timeout** — Kronk's streaming inference requires a context deadline. If the incoming ctx has none (most web/CLI request contexts do not), a generous cap is added via `context.WithTimeout`. An existing deadline is always honoured.\n3. **Translate the message format** — `toKronkMessages` and `toKronkTools` convert `llm.Message`/`llm.ToolSpec` values into the `model.D` map shape the Kronk SDK expects. The tools key is omitted entirely when the slice is empty because llama.cpp's chat template rejects a null tools field.\n4. **Bridge the stream** — `bridge` drains Kronk's `ChatResponse` channel and re-emits `llm.Chunk` values, firing `cancel` when the stream ends.\n\n`Embed` (line 74) follows the same lazy-load pattern for the embedding model slot.\n\n**Tour 03** shows the agent loop that consumes the `<-chan llm.Chunk` returned here."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/librt.go",
      "line": 32,
      "title": "11.6 — Runtime install, fail-closed",
      "description": "```go\nfunc InstallRuntime(ctx context.Context, processor string, log libs.Logger) error\n```\n\n`InstallRuntime` is the **owner-initiated** path to get the llama.cpp native library onto disk. It is never called on boot — the binary starts without a runtime and tells the owner to install one if inference is attempted without it.\n\nKey design points:\n- The pinned version is `runtimeVersion = \"b9664\"` (the llama.cpp build the Kronk SDK was developed against). Changing this constant is a **reviewed code change**, not a runtime config knob.\n- After the SDK download, `verifyInstall` checks the sha256 manifest (`runtime_sums.json`, embedded in the binary). A mismatch returns an error — the install **fails closed**.\n- The SDK refuses to install into a non-empty `LibRoot()` without a `version.json` marker (it treats it as read-only). `InstallRuntime` sidesteps this by staging each download in a fresh temp dir under `LibRoot()`, then atomically moving the finished `<os>/<arch>/<processor>/` bundle into place. This allows multiple processor variants (cpu and vulkan) to coexist.\n- `RuntimeInstalled()` / `RuntimeInstalledFor(processor)` (in `runtime.go`, line 11/19) are stat-only checks — they never dlopen anything (each stats `libllama.so` under the resolved `resolveLibDir` path). `resolveProcessor` in `main.go` uses `RuntimeInstalledFor` on boot to degrade a saved/env processor choice back to cpu when that variant is not actually installed, so a missing vulkan runtime never strands inference; the Models page (`internal/web/models.go`) uses the same check to refuse selecting an uninstalled variant.\n\nCPU is the default processor. `BALAUR_PROCESSOR=vulkan` switches to the Vulkan offload variant; the host Vulkan driver is host setup, not the binary's concern.\n\nAGENTS.md: *the engine never downloads anything on boot.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/officialmodel.go",
      "line": 31,
      "title": "11.7 — The EU model catalog",
      "description": "```go\nfunc OfficialModels() []OfficialModel\n```\n\n`OfficialModels` returns the curated, owner-installable GGUF catalog. Today it contains Qwen3.5 2B (small/fast) and Qwen3.5 4B (balanced, recommended), both pinned to exact HuggingFace URLs and sha256 checksums.\n\nThree design invariants encoded here:\n\n1. **A model addition is a reviewed code change.** The catalog is a slice literal in source — there is no runtime registry file to edit, no admin endpoint to call. Adding or changing an entry means a PR with a real URL and a verified sha256.\n2. **Tool-call correctness is a gate.** The comment explains that Gemma 4 E4B was removed because its bundled chat template crashes when tools are present (a known upstream llama.cpp bug). Every new entry must be confirmed to tool-call correctly under the embedded engine before it goes in.\n3. **Download verifies the pin.** `OfficialByKey` retrieves an entry by its stable key (`\"small\"`, `\"medium\"`) and the download path (`modelget.Fetch`) passes `SHA256` as `wantSHA256` — a mismatch deletes the `.part` file and returns an error, so a stale pin fails closed.\n\nThe AGENTS.md EU-sovereignty rule applies here: the catalog lists only locally-runnable GGUF models. Cloud providers belong in `internal/llm/presets.go` (Mistral today, EU-jurisdiction only)."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/kronk/modelget/modelget.go",
      "line": 37,
      "title": "11.8 — Model download",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Fetch(ctx context.Context, url, destDir, fileName, wantSHA256 string,\n    wantSize int64, token string, onProgress func(Progress)) (finalPath string, err error)\n```\n\n`Fetch` is the resumable GGUF downloader. CGO-free, stdlib only. Its contract:\n\n- **Resume via HTTP Range** — if a `<fileName>.part` file already exists, Fetch sets `Range: bytes=<size>-` and appends to it. A cancelled download can be resumed from where it stopped.\n- **Streaming sha256** — the hash is computed over the bytes as they arrive, not after; there is no second read pass. On mismatch the `.part` is deleted (never renamed) and an error is returned.\n- **Atomic rename** — only on sha256 match does the `.part` become the final file. A partial file can never be mistaken for a complete one.\n- **Free-space pre-flight** — if `wantSize > 0`, Fetch checks available bytes (via an injectable `freeBytesFunc` seam for tests) before touching the network.\n- **Bearer token safety** — the optional `token` is sent only in the `Authorization` header, never embedded in the URL, never logged. `wantSHA256` is logged on mismatch but the token is not.\n- **Progress throttling** — `onProgress` is called at most roughly every 250ms so the SSE stream to the UI stays light.\n\nThis downloader is used for both official catalog models (from HuggingFace) and the runtime library install path. The same fail-closed sha256 discipline applies to both.\n\nCross-reference: the opt-in remote `llm.OpenAIClient` (`internal/llm/openai.go`) handles cloud turns; its API key is stored on-box in the PocketBase `llm_config` record and is never logged. Embeddings are always served by the local Kronk engine regardless of which chat provider is active."
    }
  ]
}
